Control Statements

3

So far all programming code we implemented were sequential.

That means when we execute our programs, all the code in the program got executed line by line sequentially.

There are two types of control statements which can change the sequence of running code

    • Selection structures (Lecture Day 2)

- Selects which line of code to run next

    • Repetition structures

- Decides how many times to repeatedly run a given line/s of code.

Repetition Structures

5

    • Repetition structures let you execute the same code over and over again.
    • loop always applies to a block of code. Similar to a selection structure.
    • Every line in a block of code has the same minimum amount of indentation.
    • Beginning and end of a block of code can be identified by looking at the number of spaces at the front of the lines.

for loop

8

    • Python for loop behaves slightly different from for loops in other programming languages.
    • They can be used to iterate over a sequence of a list, string, tuple, set, array, data frame (sequences will be introduced in Topics 4 and 5, and later).
    • The for loop is also useful for looping over a series of items using the range function.

for loop using range function

9

    • for statement begins with the for keyword, followed by a new variable name, followed by the in keyword, followed by the range function with an integer argument, and ending with a colon.
    • For loop with range function can be used to iterate some integer variable in increasing or decreasing order.
    • The sequence is created using range(low_bound, up_bound)

VIT1102 - Introduction to Object Oriented Programming

while loop contd..

18

    • The while statement marks the beginning of a loop and has a : colon after the condition.
    • Statements that end with a colon expect a new block on the next line.
    • When the execution reaches a while statement, it evaluates the condition next to the while keyword.
    • the condition evaluates to True, the execution moves inside the following block (called the while-block).
    • the condition evaluates to False, the execution moves all the way past the while-block.

Programming errors and Debugging

33

    • Errors in a program can occur due to several different reasons.
    • When typing, syntax has to follow Python language rules.

(computer is a machine, so cannot guess! – even a single missing comma is confusing!)

    • computer program will always follow the instructions given. Hence the instructions needs to be precise.
    • program will do what you tell it to do. But what you tell the program to do might not be the same as what you wanted the program to do.
    • programming, any of these errors are called ‘bugs’.
    • The process of getting rid of such bugs is called ‘debugging’.

Note: Refer to Chapter 7 page 62 of (Sweigart 2015)

Topic 3 _ Repetition Structures

VIT1102 - Introduction to Object Oriented Programming

Types of Errors

34

There are 3 types of bugs that can exist in a program.

    • Syntax errors
      • program will not run with syntax errors.
      • Very easy to locate as the editor will display a red line.
      • Example: Typos such as missing comma.
    • Run time errors
      • Program will run with these errors. But will stop/crash in the middle.
      • Example: if the program is trying to write data to a non existing file.
    • Semantic/logic errors
      • Program will run without any problem but will not give the expected result.
      • Semantic errors are difficult to locate.
      • Debugging tools will help to solve.

Topic 3 _ Repetition Structures

VIT1102 - Introduction to Object Oriented Programming

Debugging

35

Debugging is the process of finding and fixing errors in computer programs.

A debugger is a program that lets you step through your code one line at a time in the same order that Python executes them.

The debugger also shows you what values are stored in variables at each step.

Note: Refer to Chapter 7 page 62 of (Sweigart 2015)

Using PyCharm debugger

36

    • debugging, you will be stepping through your code.
    • This is time consuming to apply to entire program.
    • You can set break points to avoid unnecessary code tracing and reach a point just before where you guess the bug is.
    • set/ or remove a break point click at the start of a line and press ctrl + F8
    • Then debugger can be activated by selecting Debug command in Run menu.
